</p>

<h3 id="whos-anonymous">Who writes as anonymous?</h3>

<p>
  Anonymous posting is an option for logged in user if they wish to protect their identity.
  If a poster elects to do this then we null out every field that could identify them.
  We don't create the mirage of pseudo-privacy in our backend.
</p>

<h3 id="losing-ownership">If I choose to write an article as anonymous, why do I lose ownership/ability to edit it?</h3>

<p>
  The reason this happens is because this database is specifically designed for privacy.
  Every website that even remotely resembles this one will have user data and content data separated into tables.
  Take for example the Users and Posts tables:
</p>

