<p>
  Notice that in the Posts table, under the "Author" column, the name of the user isn't stored, but
  their ID is instead. That's how every single application in the world identifies a user. So when Jesse
  goes back to revise his proof of why P=NP, the site can recognize it's him and allow him to edit it,
  and not Walter White.
</p>

<p>
  The thing is, when websites allow you to do this most of the time, they will just hide who originally wrote it
  from everyone else and keep the truth hidden in the database. The problem with this is the owner can still see it.
  To give a solid guarantee of privacy is to not store that column at all; otherwise the owner of the
  site could look up who wrote what.
</p>

<p>
  This also includes big brother or legal entities. The person running the show can have the best intentions for the users,
  but if big brother comes knocking on the door the owner has to answer the call and give up the database. If that ID is there,
  it's basically over at that step; they get what they want. If you don't store it though, then you can protect your users far
  more. Any legal entity that's given power to request the database of this site will gain no further information about who said what.
</p>

<p>
  Of course, it comes with a cost too. If you write something down anonymously, the site can't identify
  who was the original author and therefore cannot let anyone edit it. You also can't delete it, because
  there's no way to tell if you owned it already.
</p>

